<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence on 'Heat' submitted to the Select Committee on Energy and Climate Change</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Paul MK Dodgshun (HOT04)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1:  Scientific Theory:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">In respect of heat pumps the draft RHI policy, published on the 12</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> July, is scientifically incorrect on two counts.  It disregards the consequences of :- </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1.1:  Carnot's Law [</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">1:</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#x200e;</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">]  , and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1.2:  Ohm's Law, I2R losses and power factor [</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">2: 3: 4:</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2:  Domestic Heat Pumps:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.1:  Maximum Efficiency:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The policy should mandat</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">e the use of the most Carnot efficient pumps that are commercially available.  These are pumps of the air-to-air type and they can achieve a headline Coefficient of Performance (COP) that is greater than 5.5.  All heat pump types with lower comparable COPs</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> should be suppressed by the policy, unless extenuating circumstances apply; this is a consequence of 1.1:.  If implemented, this proposal will halve electricity bills compared to inefficient air-to-water pumps, currently promoted by the RHPP and proposed </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">by the draft RHI.  Failure to implement this proposal will result in double the Carbon burn for running domestic heat pumps.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.2:  Capacity:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Each household to be allowed only 1kWe of Grid supplied heat pump capacity.  Spread over 8.6 million households th</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">at produces a maximum generation demand of 8.6GW (10% of current grid capacity).  This maximum demand will appear for most of the winter as a continuous (modulated air-to-air heat pumps run continuously) load on the electricity grid.  Homes with pre-existi</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ng fossil fired boilers should retain those boilers, new homes have them fitted where practicable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3:  National Gas and Electricity Grid and Distribution:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.1:  Electricity Grid and Distribution:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.2: is a consequence of 1.2: in respect of the National El</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ectricity Grid and distribution network.  The 1kWe of electricity proposed in 2.2: will be doubly effective, if supplied to efficient air-to-air pumps as compared to air-to-water pumps. Supplied to air-to-air pumps, 1kWe will supply about 4kW of heat per p</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ump at freezing (0C).  If full-sized, inefficient air-to-water pumps are permitted, maximum generation capacity on the grid may need to be double the current (about 86GW) level.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Doubled generation capacity means doubled conductor cross-sections and doub</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">led transformer capacities in the whole of the distribution network, if line and transformer losses, currently 8%, are not to rise.  Grid line losses, currently 3%, may be prevented from rising by higher grid voltages and/or greater conductor cross-section</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">s, but transformer replacement will be needed.  Localised gas fired generation, mostly in the south, should require less long distance transportation of electricity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.2:  Gas Grid:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">There is an interaction between the gas grid and the electricity grid, as</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> gas is diverted from </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">domestic consumption to gas fired electricity generation.  Ideal sites for this generation  would be where electricity grid substations and gas grid pipes are co-located, along with adequate water.  The appropriate percentage of diver</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">sion is the question; it does not have to be 0% or 100%, and that is a cardinal error in the draft RHI policy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">[1:]  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carnot's_theorem_(thermodynamics)</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#x200e;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">[2:]  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohm's_l</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">aw  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">[3:]  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copper_loss </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">[4:]</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_factor</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">[5:]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">4:  The government is currently subsidising and encouraging the sale of heat pumps that use twice as much electricity as the best alternative.  That means double s</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ized electricity bills that will continue for the life of the equipment; the subsidies do not cover the losses.  The subsidies are an expensive trap for the pump owner and a waste of money for the taxpayer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">5:  The draft RHI policy should be redrafted to</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> offer to give every household a 1kWe heat pump of the highest Carnot Efficiency air-to-air type.  This would cost less than £1000+fitting per pump.  All other subsidies for heat pumps should be withdrawn.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">6:  Soon, the government will have to ban the </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">installation of heat pumps greater than 1kWe in size and then only one per house, unless they are supported by self-generation.  Any additional heat load is to be supplied by fossil fired equipment (boilers, stoves, fires or whatever) or night storage heat</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ers.  In most cases, this is likely to be pre-existing equipment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7:  My proposal, 1kwE per house, requires a capped 10% increase in generation capacity (8.6GW).  Inefficient(x2) full-sized(x10) pumps could require a 200% increase, alongside massive grid</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> reinforcement.  There is no economic case for :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.1:  a 200% increase in grid capacity,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.2:  a 200% increase in generation capacity, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.3:  a full-sized inefficient fleet of 8.6 million heat pumps;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">that runs at high load for only a few cold days in t</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">he year, instead :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.4:  no increase in grid capacity, albeit with a few days of increased grid losses,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.5:  a 10% increase in generation capacity, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">7.6:  a 1kWe air-to-air heat pump per house</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">suffices to achieve the objective, a minimum Carbon burn. </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">At sub-zero temperatures, heat pumps become inefficient and taken over the full CCGT/grid/distribution/heat pump route they become no more efficient than boilers and much poorer than boilers, if grid reinforcement is not extensive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">8:  Heat pumps have an</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">other serious efficiency problem: part load running.  When run at low to very low part loads, even the best modulated pumps, have very poor Carnot efficiencies.  When sized for heating a house at minimum design temperatures, perhaps -15C, they inevitably r</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">un at low to very low part loads at more average temperatures.  To combat this problem, small pumps need to be fitted that can hold a house (20C) temperature down to about freezing (0C) ambient temperature.  My proposal also does this; a 1kW(electrical)/4k</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">W(thermal) heat pump will hold the temperature of my house at my winter quarter average (100kWh per day, stated by my gas bill) load, based on continuous (4x24=96kWh per day) running.  My house is a five bed, detached with double glazing, loft and cavity i</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">nsulation; if it works for my house, then it will for 95% of the others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">9:  The most efficient heat pump is a good air-to-air pump, running continuously at full load, with a minimum temperature drop across its refrigerant circuit.  Anything else involve</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">s wasted electricity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2: Introduction:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.1: I am a retired mechanical engineer from the nuclear power industry.  After working at Longannet, Hunterston 'B' and Heysham Power Stations, I joined the staff of </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">a small engineering team preparing and evaluating nuclear safety cases in support of nuclear power stations in the south-east of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.2: In June, I was cold-called by a company who wished to sell me a heat pump.  I agreed to accept a sales engineer's visit to my house.  When the sales engineer asked for my order, I responded with 'due diligence first'.  Due diligence continues.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.3:</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> The insights gained allow me to address the committee's following questions :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.3.1: </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Q1 - Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">A1 - Because it has got the fundamental science wrong.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.3.2: </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Q2 - What are the relative merits o</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">f using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">A2 – Capacity balance should be about 90% gas/fossil fuel, 10% air-to-air heat pump.  Heat production balance is then about 10% gas/foss</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">il fuel, 90% air-to-air heat pump. Use of gas/fossil fuel occurs when it is as efficient as or more efficient than the heat pump, taken over the full CCGT/grid/distribution/heat pump route (i.e. at sub-zero temperatures).  This balance has the minimum Carb</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">on burn and the minimum capital cost over the generation/grid/distribution/heat pump route as compared to the boiler route.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2.3.3: </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Q3 - How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">A3 – In respect of heat pumps, disastrous unless totall</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">y redrafted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3: Facts:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.1:  Carnot's Law:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Carnot's Law states that the theoretical maximum efficiency of a heat pump is equal to Thot/(Thot-Tcold) where temperatures are stated in degrees absolute (e.g. fr</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">eezing is 273C and boiling is 373C)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">COP 5/30=(273+30)/(30-5)=303/25=12.12</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">COP 5/60=(273+60)/(60-5)=333/55=6.05</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">12.12/6.05= 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">This is the basis of the statement that air-to-air pumps that blow air at 30C are twice as efficient as air-to-water pumps that use</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> hot wet radiators at 60C.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Real heat pumps deliver less than the theoretical maximum, perhaps 0.4 to 0.6 forms the main range.  Part load coefficients at loads below 50% start to deteriorate rapidly to 0 at 0% part load  e.g. If the theoretical Carnot eff</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">iciency is x, the pump factor is 0.5 and the part load factor is also 0.5, then the overall efficiency of the pump is x/4.  The Carnot efficiency of resistive heating is 1.0.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.2:  I2R Losses in </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transformers and Cables on the National Grid and Distribution Networks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Current losses on the National Grid are about 3%.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Current losses on the Distribution Network are about 8%.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">If 8.6 million homes have 10kW(electrical) heat pumps fitted, then this is a </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">capacity demand on the grid system of 86GW, approximately equal to the currently installed capacity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">If this doubles line and transformer currents, then the I2R losses quadruple to (3+8)*4=44%.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The I2R losses heat the lines and transformers which have the</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">rmal overload protection.  At some point the protection will start 'tripping' and supply breakers will open.  The result may be blackouts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Major reinforcement of the grid and distribution networks would be needed, right down to the 415V transformers that </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">supply houses.  If the cabling needs reinforcing, that means digging up the roads.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">My current domestic electrical load is about 10kWh per day, all year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">My current domestic gas load is an average of about 100kWh per day during winter and 10kWh per day in </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">the summer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Transferring all my winter demand to the electrical supply will increase my peak demand on the electrical supply by a factor of about 11.  I have no reason to think that my consumption is atypical.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">10/11ths of that higher electrical load will</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> be continuous over the colder days, with peaks in the remaining 1/11 that mirror the current 24 hour demand curve of the grid.  When a pre-existing grid peak combines with a heat pump load peak, then what is the demand on, 1: local supply transformers, an</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">d 2:  power station capacity?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">It is the local supply transformers that receive the greatest increase.  The power station load rises by a factor of 2 but the domestic supply transformers experience an 11 fold rise.  Local supply transformers are sized 'sto</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">chastically'; they are already too small for all the total installed load in the attached houses and presumably their supply cables are similarly sized.  An 11-fold increase in cable cross-sections and transformers is predicted on the 415V system.  I2R los</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ses have a major effect on the draft RHI policy.  There has to be a better way and there is:  the 1kWe capacity air-to-air heat pump, installed one per house.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3: Efficiencies and Coefficients of </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Performance (COPs)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The draft domestic RHI policy is about the comparative efficiency of two routes :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1:  generator/grid/distribution/heat pump, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2:  domestic boiler.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The best gas turbine generators achieve about 0.65 efficiency</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Big steam turbines </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">achieve about 0.35</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Grid losses are currently about 3%, so 0.97</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Distribution losses are currently about 8%, so 0.92</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The efficiency of domestic pure resistive heating from :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: gas generated grid supplied electricity is .65x.97x.92x1.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.58</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: steam turb</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ine, grid supplied electricity is .35x.97x.92x1.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.31</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The highest(65%) generation efficiencies come from CCGT plant; the highest heat pump headline COPs(5.5+) come from air-to-air pumps .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Clearly, the most efficient overall system requires the highest</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> generation efficiencies, coupled with the lowest grid and distribution losses and the heat pumps with the highest COPs (.65x.97x.92x5.5= 3.19).  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The poorest system is steam turbine electricity, through overloaded grid/distribution to a resistive load (.</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">35x.86x.72x1.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.22).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">The ratio of best to worst is 3.19/0.22=14.5. </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> It is a very large number and graphically illustrates the potential benefit of heat pumps, PROVIDED  that ALL the technology involved is operating at optimum efficiency.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1: Generati</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2: grid, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3: distribution, and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4: heat pump </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">efficiencies have to be individually maximised to achieved the combined desired result, whilst noting that the gas grid can help in a major way.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Efficiency</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Tables:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Note:  This is purely an efficiency analysis; it does not consider prices</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.19 is the ceiling efficiency for this exercise.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.1:  Heat Pump COPs at -15C are poor, so 1.5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.1.1:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.97x.92x1.5</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.87</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">efficiency: equal</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Conclusion: Fossil fired boilers are just as efficient as heat pumps and that is before heavy line losses are considered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.1.2:  If grid and distribution currents double, then line and transformer losses quadruple (so-called I squared</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> R losses) :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">This also implies the same line and transformer losses for all the grid load, not just the heat pump load.  This comment applies to all subsequent cases (double grid/distribution losses).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.86x.72x1.5</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.62 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.65x.72x.44x1.5= 0.31)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump poorer by 0.23 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.54)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Conclusion: Fossil fired boilers are more efficient than heat pumps by a clear margin.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.1.3:  With electricity supplied by steam turbine :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .35x.86x.72x1.5</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">0.33 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.35x.72x.44x1.5= 0.16)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump poorer by 0.52</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.69)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Conclusion: The use of heat pumps with heavy line losses is a non-starter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Overall Conclusion:  Everyone should be using a fossil fired </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">boiler at temperatures of -15C because doubling the grid/distribution system and installing matching gas generator capacity is a very expensive business, particularly when you consider that it is only fully used on a few coldest days of the year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.2: </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Heat Pump COPs assumed to be 2.0</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.2.1:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.97x.92x2.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.16</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> better by 0.3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">To achieve this, the grid and distribution systems must double in capacity, if future heat pump capacity equals current </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">grid capacity (8.6 million homes @10kW each=86GW).  On capital cost grounds this must surely be uneconomic for so small a gain?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.2.2:  If grid and distribution currents double, then line and transformer losses quadruple (so-called I squared R losses) </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">:-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.86x.72x2.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.82 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.65x.72x.44x2.0= 0.41)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: equal for all practical purposes </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.44)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.2.3:  With electricity supplied by steam turbine :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .35x.86x.72x2.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.44 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.35x.72x.</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">44x2.0= 0.22)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump poorer by 0.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.64)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Q: So, having invested in :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1:  doubling the capacity of the National Grid and distribution systems,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2:  8.6 million domestic heat pumps with a COP of 2.</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">0, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3:  the gas generators to supply them;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">what have you achieved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">A:  An overall increase in efficiency of 0.3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Does this outweigh the capital costs of pumps, generators and grid/distribution reinforcement, bearing in mind the very low capacity utilisat</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ion?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.3:  Heat Pump COPs assumed to be 3.0</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.3.1:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.97x.92x3.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.74</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">better by 0.9</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">To achieve this, the grid, distribution and generation systems must double in capacity, if future heat pump</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> capacity equals current grid capacity (8.6 million homes @10kW each=86GW).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.3.2:  If grid and distribution currents double, then line and transformer losses quadruple (so-called I squared R losses) :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.86x.72x3.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.24 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.65x.72x.44x3.0= 0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.61)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> better by 0.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.24)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.3.3:  With electricity supplied by steam turbine :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .35x.86x.72x3.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.67 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.35x.72x.44x3.0= 0.33)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberat