ty utilisation?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">You need a COP of greater than 3.0 to turn </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">off a gas boiler and use a heat pump because electricity costs three times as much as gas, but that statement ignores capital costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.4:  Heat Pump COPs assumed to be 4.0</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Air-to-air heat pumps with a headline COP of 5.5+ may deliver a COP of 4 at </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">freezing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.4.1:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.97x.92x4.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 2.3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> better by 1.45</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.4.2:  If grid and distribution currents double, then line and transformer losses quadruple (so-called I squared R losses) :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.86x.</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">72x4.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.65 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.65x.72x.44x4.0= 0.82)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> better by 0.8</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(Comparative efficiency: equal – what you gain on pump efficiency is lost on heating the grid wires and distribution cables)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.4.3:  With </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">electricity supplied by steam turbine :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .35x.86x.72x4.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.89 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.35x.72x.44x4.0= 0.44)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: equal for all practical purposes. </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.41)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.5:  Heat Pump COPs assumed to be 5.0</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Air-to-air heat </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">pumps with a headline COP of 5.5+ do not deliver this COP at low temperatures, so this table is beyond the range of interest for low temperatures.  However this COP is delivered at the rated temperature (usually 7C).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.5.1:  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.97x.92x5.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 2.9</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump  </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">better by 2.05</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.5.2:  If grid and distribution currents double, then line and transformer losses quadruple (so-called I squared R losses) :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .65x.86x.72x5.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 2.06 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.65x.72x.44x5.0= 1.03)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boi</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">better by 1.2</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump better by 0.18)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">3.3.5.3:  With electricity supplied by steam turbine :-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: .35x.86x.72x5.0</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.11 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(.35x.72x.44x5.0= 0.55)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> better by 0.25</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(pump poorer by 0.3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.6:  Part Load Factor</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">COPs are reduced by part load running.  This is a potent source of pump efficiency problems when pumps operate at below half power.  At 0 part load the efficiency becomes 0%.  All pumps that are sized to deli</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ver the full heat load of a house at -15, or -10C when pump COPs are reduced, are going to normally operate in a low or very low part load condition at more usual temperatures.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">If the part load factor becomes 0.5. at something like 25% part load, then t</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">ake the efficiencies calculated in 3.3.5.1:, that are the highest of all cases, and (1:=2.9) becomes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">1: 2.9x0.5 </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 1.45</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">2: boiler</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">= 0.85</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">Comparative efficiency: pump </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">better by 0.6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">but the comparative efficiency before was pump </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">better by 2.05</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">major 1.45 reduction is a consequence of part load running.  The use of one heat pump, sized to a full house heat load at -10C or -15C, to cover the full load range from 100% to 0% is hopelessly inefficient, because the pump will spend most of its operatin</span><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">g hours in the low part load condition.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">______________________________________________</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Liberation Serif'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>